07152nam a22012495i 9781487539719DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222022onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875397197 a10.3138/97814875397192doi  a(DE-B1597)618975  a(OCoLC)1286078477  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHT384.L29 7aARC0100002bisacsh04a307.7609822300aBeyond the Megacity :bNew Dimensions of Peripheral Urbanization in Latin America /ced. by Nadine Reis, Michael Lukas. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b31 b&w illustrations, 11 b7w maps,1 b&w figure, 8 b&w tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGlobal Suburbanisms0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeyond the Megacity connects and reconnects the global debate on the contemporary urban condition to the Latin American tradition of seeing, considering, and theorizing urbanization from the margins. It develops the approach of "peripheral urbanization" as a way to integrate the theoretical agendas belonging to global suburbanisms, neo-marxist accounts of planetary urbanization, and postcolonial urban studies, and to move urban theory closer to the complexity and diversity of urbanization in the Global South. From an interdisciplinary perspective, Beyond the Megacity investigates the natures, causes, implications, and politics of current urbanization processes in Latin America. The book draws on case studies from various countries across the region covering different theoretical and disciplinary approaches from the fields of geography, anthropology, sociology, urban studies, agrarian studies, and urban and regional planning, and is written by academics, journalists, practitioners, and scholar-activists. Beyond the Megacity unites these unique perspectives by shifting attention to the places, processes, practices, and bodies of knowledge that have often been neglected in the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aUrbanizationzLatin AmericavCase studies. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh  aLatin America.  aactivism.  adecolonial.  aeconomy.  aextractivism.  amovements.  aperipheries.  apolitics.  apostcolonial.  arurality.  asocial.  asururb.  asururban.  atheory.  aurban.  aurbanism.  aurbanization.1 aAlfaro, Claudia Fonseca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArboleda, Martín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarbieri, Alisson F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayón, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldeira, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastriota, Rodrigo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurán, Gustavo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFelicien, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolda-Pongratz, Kathrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLukas, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLukas, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMason-Deese, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMenoscal, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoeller, Hannah-Hunt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOjima, Ricardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReis, Nadine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReis, Nadine, eeditor.